Thanks a lot for the quick feedback. I agree, this does look strange. This is just a test fixture code, it does not matter much which of supported annotations are listed here.
Let me kindly a related question though, because I think I have a use case for this strange combination. Consider below:
class MySelection {
  long id;
  // ...
}

class MyForm {
  // @Nullable?
  @NotNull
  MySelection selection; 
}
We generate TypeScript definitions corresponding to the Java beans above. When doing that, we assume everything to be kind of a @Nonnull by default, so that the TypeScript interfaces are strict, nicely require initialisation of all the fields on creation, and guarantee a value presence when are being read.
However, when it comes to binding a form with a combo-box to the selection field, the following is expected:

The combo-box is empty by default, unless an initial value is provided or selected by the user. That’s why I’d add @Nullable to make the generated TypeScript type interface for MyForm allow selection to be undefined. We need to explicitly opt-out from the “all the data must be defined” assumption.
The empty combo-box errors when submitted. That’s why I’d add the @NotNull validation constrain.

Do you have any suggestions for how to more reasonably express that kind of a field in Java?

From a java point of view combining both annotation doesn't make sense (and probably (not tested; just a guess) some validation frameworks are going to complain about it). My understanding for this kind of TS "magic" is that "java is always first". Meaning that I create the bean / pojo / dto / object with the annotations or re-use an existing piece of code and just add vaadin as presentation layer.
Examples:
class Person {

  String doctorate;

  @NotNull
  String name;

  @NotNull
  Address mainAddress;

  List<Address> secondaryAddresses;

}

class Address {

  @NotNull
  String street;
  // ... and more
}
Given this example; I would expect the following from vaadin to generate:

optional text-input for doctorate
required text-input for name
required layout for mainAddress (in this example a simple text-field)
button "Add Secondary Address" which creates a new layout for an address input + a "Delete this secondary address button"

or am I mistaken that the Java Bean Validation says that every property is optional until otherwise specified via annotation?
Edit: Currently with Binder you can specify "asRequired()" and the default value passed from server side won't break the UI. Meaning if it is null the combo box is just empty, otherwise it's filled with the current selected item. The TS world should be able to handle such cases as well. (without adding not intuitive annotations ;))

@knoobie very good point. Thanks again for your detailed response.
@Haprog yes, that’s the use case.
Looks like it is a problem in the way our existing TS magic works. Perhaps have to reconsider our defaults in there to make our generated TypeScript fields nullable by default, as they work in Java. This change is not in scope of this PR, so to be done separately.
For now I removed the annotation from the fixture.

